analysis.info:
RELAX (a random effects test of selection relaxation) uses a random effects branch-site model framework to test whether a set of 'Test' branches evolves under relaxed selection relative to a set of 'Reference' branches (R), as measured by the relaxation parameter (K).
                                                Version 2.1 adds a check for stability in K estimates to try to mitigate convergence problems
analysis.citation: RELAX: Detecting Relaxed Selection in a Phylogenetic Framework (2015). Mol Biol Evol 32 (3): 820-832
analysis.authors: Sergei L Kosakovsky Pond, Ben Murrell, Steven Weaver and Temple iGEM / UCSD viral evolution group
analysis.requirements: in-frame codon alignment and a phylogenetic tree, with at least two groups of branches defined using the {} notation (one group can be defined as all unlabeled branches)
